When we write Java code, a lot happens behind the scenes in the JVM. Understanding memory flow helps us write efficient and scalable applications.

Hereâ€™s a structured breakdown:
ğŸ”¹ 1. Memory Areas in JVM
When a Java program runs, JVM divides memory into different areas:
1. Stack Memory
Stores method calls, local variables, references to objects.
Memory is allocated per thread (each thread has its own stack).
2. Heap Memory (shared across all threads)
Stores objects and class instances.
Divided into:
 1. Young Generation â†’ new objects, subdivided into:
 a. Eden Space â†’ where new objects are created.
 b. Survivor (S0 & S1) â†’ where objects survive GC cycles before moving to Old Gen.
 2. Old Generation (Tenured) â†’ long-lived objects.
 3. Metaspace â†’ stores class metadata, method info, runtime constant pool (replaced PermGen in Java 8+).

ğŸ”¹ 2. String Pool
Located inside the Heap (Method Area/Metaspace).
Stores unique string literals for memory efficiency.
Example:
String s1 = "Hello";
String s2 = "Hello"; 
Sysout(s1 == s2); // true â†’ both refer to same object
If you use new String("Hello"), a new object is created in the heap, not in the pool.

ğŸ”¹ 3. Constant Pool
Part of Metaspace.
Stores class-level constants (numbers, final values, method references, class names).
Two types:
Class Constant Pool (specific to each class).
Runtime Constant Pool (RCP) â†’ created when class is loaded at runtime.

ğŸ”¹ 4. References in Java
Objects in Heap are managed by references:
Strong Reference â†’ normal references (String s = "Hi";) â†’ GC wonâ€™t remove until null.
Soft Reference â†’ eligible for GC only when memory is low.
Weak Reference â†’ GC removes as soon as no strong reference exists.

ğŸ”¹ 5. GC Process
GC runs automatically to free Heap memory:
Mark Phase â†’ Finds objects that are still reachable (via references).
Sweep Phase â†’ Removes objects not marked (unreachable).
Compact Phase â†’ Rearranges remaining objects to avoid memory fragmentation.
Example:
String s = new String("Java");
s = null; // "Java" object becomes unreachable â†’ GC cleans it

ğŸ”¹ 6. Types of GCs
Serial GC â†’ Single-threaded, simple.
Parallel GC â†’ Multi-threaded, good for throughput.
CMS (Concurrent Mark-Sweep) â†’ Reduces pause time, works alongside app.
G1 GC (Garbage First) â†’ Splits Heap into regions, balances pause & throughput.

